# AI Native Enterprises Are First a New Form of Organization

If enterprise SaaS software is mainly about managing “human organizational structures and workflows,” then the new question an AI Native enterprise needs to face is this: how do humans and Agents form an organization together?

This is becoming one of my clearest thoughts as I keep thinking about enterprise AI transformation: an Agent should not just be a tool entry point, and it should not just be a chat assistant sitting next to an employee. If it is going to truly participate in enterprise operations, it has to enter the organizational structure and become a new kind of digital organizational member.

In the past, enterprise organizational capability was mostly built around people. When a person joins a company, they have a department, a role, responsibilities, permissions, reporting relationships, performance evaluation, and accountability.  Through this structure, companies break down complex work and allow different people to collaborate.

But if, in the future, a large amount of analysis, planning, execution, and summarization is done by Agents, companies can no longer treat Agents as robots floating outside the organization. An Agent without an organizational position will struggle to participate in enterprise work in a stable way. It does not know who it represents, what its responsibility boundary is, when it should act on its own, and when it must hand the decision back to a human.

So I believe that in an AI Native enterprise, there will be an Agent organization that runs in parallel with the human organization. This Agent organization is not simply about giving every employee an AI assistant. It is about allowing different Agents to become clear digital roles. Some Agents may be closer to managers, responsible for understanding goals, breaking down direction, and identifying risks. Some may be closer to business experts, responsible for analyzing data, forming proposals, and coordinating resources. Others may be closer to executors, responsible for processing files, organizing materials, generating drafts, and following up on results.

These Agents should not be flat and isolated. They should have hierarchy, division of labor, and collaboration relationships. A strategic Agent can break a goal down for business Agents. A business Agent can then turn that into specific actions for execution Agents. Human owners confirm direction, authorize resources, review results, and take responsibility at key moments. This is different from how many AI tools are used today. A lot of AI usage is still based on “a human asks, AI answers,” or a user manually creates multiple Agents and assigns tasks among them. But real enterprise work is not just question-and- answer, nor is it merely splitting work into several tasks. Work flows and moves across an organization. After a goal is proposed, someone needs to understand it, break down the path, judge the resources needed, assign tasks, follow up on progress, handle blockers, review results, and summarize experience. If an Agent is only a chat assistant, it is hard for it to support this kind of continuous organizational work.

Once Agents enter the organization, the role of humans will also change. I do not fully agree with the simple statement that AI will replace people. A more accurate way to say it is: AI will change the center of gravity of human work inside organizations. Many repetitive tasks, such as retrieving data, organizing information, analyzing, generating drafts, and following up, will increasingly be handled by Agents. But questions such as what goal should be set, whether a risk is acceptable, whether resources should be opened, whether a key plan should be executed, and whether the final result should be accepted still require human participation. In other words, people will gradually move away from many fragmented execution details and stand more often at the position of goal-setting, judgment, authorization, and responsibility. This does not weaken humans. It redefines the role of humans. In the past, a manager might spend a lot of time chasing data, pushing progress, and preparing reports. In the future, these tasks can be continuously handled by Agents. Humans can focus more on whether the direction is right, whether the risk is acceptable, whether organizational resources should be invested, and whether the final result matches business judgment.

In this kind of organization, Agents do not replace humans and “do everything.” They become digital extensions of humans. A person’s experience, judgment criteria, business preferences, and management style will gradually be injected into the way Agents work. A mature Agent will not merely call a model and answer questions. It will increasingly understand how a certain role works, how a certain department makes judgments, and how a certain type of task should be delivered.

So the organizational form of an AI Native enterprise may look like this: the human organization is responsible for goals, accountability, and key judgments, while the Agent organization is responsible for high-frequency execution, cross-system processing, information organization, and experience accumulation. These two organizations do not replace each other. They operate in parallel and collaborate with each other. This is also why I believe enterprise AI transformation cannot stop at “giving employees AI tools.” Tools are used by individuals. Organizations, however, can collaborate, divide labor, authorize, and accumulate knowledge. Only when Agents are placed inside the organizational structure can enterprise AI move from personal productivity improvement to organizational capability upgrade.

A real AI Native enterprise is first not a change in software form, but a change in organizational form. It is not about adding an AI chat window next to every employee. It is about allowing a group of digital organizational members, with identity, responsibility, boundaries, and collaboration relationships, to emerge inside the enterprise. Humans and Agents together form a new organizational structure, and the way the enterprise operates will change because of it.
